[[Image:Bon.jpeg|thumb|right|250px|Polish ''bon towarowy'', trade note]]
The '''''bon''''' (French Canadian, Polish) was a type of [[paper currency]] issued by merchants to meet the need for small change. Bon is an abbreviation for ''bon pour'' (French for "good for"). These notes were in wide use in the early part of the 19th century. They were sometimes referred to as "shin plasters" by [[English Canadians]]. Because of their widespread use, they are considered to be the [[History of money|precursor]] to modern [[banknotes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bankofcanada.ca/en/dollar_book/appendixb.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-27 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061003145644/http://www.bankofcanada.ca/en/dollar_book/appendixb.pdf |archivedate=2006-10-03 |df= }} Bank of Canada - Appendix B - Alternative Money</ref><ref>http://www.nunet.ca/cpms/terms.htm Canadian Paper Money Terminology</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=eGqeFWhr-5wC&pg=PA100 Money and exchange in Canada to 1900] "merchants to revive the practice of issuing bons or, as they were called by the English Canadians, “shinplasters”."</ref>

