In late European mythology and literature, a '''cambion''' {{IPAc-en|ˈ|k|æ|m|b|i|ən}} is the offspring of an [[incubus]] or [[succubus]] and a human, or of an incubus and succubus.
==Etymology== A cambion is most often depicted as the offspring of an [[incubus]] or [[succubus]] or demon of any kind, and a human. The earliest evidenced appearance of the word in this sense is in the 1818 French-Language ''[[Dictionnaire Infernal]]''. The 1825 edition of that book has the following entry: {{quote|text=''CAMBION, -- Enfants des Demons. Delancre et Bodin pensent que les démons incubes peuvent s'unir aux démones succubes, et qu'il nait de leur commerce des enfants hideux qu'on nomme cambions....''<ref>Dictionnaire Infernal, Vol. 2, Jacques Albin Simon Collin de Plancy, p.314.</ref>}}
{{quote|CAMBION, -- Child of Demons. Delancre and Bodin think that incubus demons could unite with succubus demons, and that born of their exchange were hideous children which are called cambions.....{{cn|date=August 2018}}}}
The word ''cambion'' previously appeared on an early first century AD inscription in [[Gaul]] (Roman France). Linguist Benjamin W. Forston IV opines that: {{quote|...''cambion'' is from the Celtic root ''-kamb'' 'crooked', also referring to back and forth motion and exchange. It is ultimately the source for English ''change'' via late Latin ''cambiare'', a borrowing from Celtic.<ref>Indo-European Language and Culture: An Introduction, Benjamin W. Forston IV, p. 17.</ref>}}
Given the above, it is probable that the word, as de Plancy defined it in 1818, is a cognate for [[changeling]].{{Cn|date=August 2018}}
==In the ''Malleus Maleficarum''== The ''[[Malleus Maleficarum]]'' does not use the word but states that demons, including the incubus and the succubus, are incapable of reproduction:
{{quote|text=Moreover, to beget a child is the act of a living body, but devils cannot bestow life upon the bodies they assume; because life formally proceeds only from the [[soul]], and the act of generation is the act of the physical organs which have bodily life. Therefore bodies which are assumed in this way cannot either beget or bear.<ref name=Malleus>[[Malleus Maleficarum]], Part I, Question III</ref>}}
Because of this inability to create or nurture life, the method of the creation of a cambion is necessarily protracted. A succubus will have sex with a human male and so acquire a sample of his [[semen|sperm]]. This she will then pass on to an incubus. The incubus will, in his turn, transfer the sperm to a human female and thus impregnate her.
{{quote|text=Yet it may be said that these devils assume a body not in order that they may bestow life upon it, but that they may by the means of this body preserve human semen, and pass the semen on to another body.<ref name=Malleus/>}}
The text goes on to discuss at great length the arguments for and against this process being possible, citing a number of biblical quotations and noted scholars in support of its arguments, and finally concludes that this is indeed the method used by such demons.
==In the ''Encyclopedia of Occultism and Parapsychology''== In the ''[[Encyclopedia of Occultism and Parapsychology]]'' the cambion is said to be the direct offspring of the incubus and the succubus, foregoing any need for human involvement. This same incarnation retained the absence of breath or a pulse until seven years of age, but was said to also have been incredibly heavy (even too heavy for a horse to carry) and to have cried upon being touched.<ref>[[Lewis Spence|Spence, Lewis]] (2000). "Cambions". In the [[Gale Group]]'s ''Encyclopedia of Occultism and Parapsychology'', p.&nbsp;148. {{ISBN|0-8103-8570-8}}.</ref>
