{{Infobox language |name=Croatian Sign Language |nativename=Hrvatski znakovni jezik |states=[[Croatia]] |speakers=13,000 |date=2014 |ref=e18 |speakers2=out of 20,000 deaf |familycolor=Sign |fam1=[[French Sign Language family|French Sign]] |fam2=[[Austro-Hungarian Sign Language|Austro-Hungarian Sign]] |fam3=[[Yugoslav Sign Language|Yugoslav Sign]] |iso3=csq |glotto=croa1242 |glottorefname=Croatian Sign Language }}
'''Croatian sign language''' ('''Hrvatski znakovni jezik''', '''HZJ'''<ref>Diane Brentari, ''Sign Languages'', Cambridge University Press, 2010. (p.xix)</ref><ref>Herbert L. Colston, Albert N. Katz; ''Figurative language comprehension'', Routledge, 2005. (p.316)</ref>) is a [[sign language]] of the [[deaf community]] in [[Croatia]].<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=csq Croatian Sign Language], [[Ethnologue]]</ref><ref>[http://www.mpr.gov.ba/userfiles/file/Biblioteka/zakoni/hr/Zakon%20o%20upotrebi%20znakovnog%20jezika/Zakon%20o%20uporabi%20znakovnog%20jezika-hr.pdf Zakon o uporabi znakovnog jezika u Bosnia i Hercegovini]</ref> It has in the past been regarded as a dialect of [[Yugoslav Sign Language]], although the dialectical diversity of the former Yugoslavia has not been assessed.<ref name=Bick>Bickford, J. Albert (2005) [http://www.sil.org/silesr/2005/silesr2005-026.pdf The Signed Languages of Eastern Europe]</ref>
The first school for the deaf in Croatia was formed in Zagreb in 1885.<ref>[http://www.eud.eu/Croatia-i-177.html Croatia profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720161018/http://www.eud.eu/Croatia-i-177.html |date=2011-07-20 }}, [[The European Union of the Deaf]]</ref> The ''Sign Language and Deaf Culture'' conference was held in [[Zagreb]], Croatia from May 3–5, 2001.<ref>Cynthia J. Kellett Bidoli, Elana Ochse; ''English in International Deaf Communication'', Peter Lang, 2008. (p.347)</ref> In 2004, a project to establish a grammar of HZJ was started by researchers at [[Purdue University]] and the [[University of Zagreb]].<ref>[http://www.sciencestorm.com/award/0345314.html A Basic Grammar of Croatian Sign Language] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716014930/http://www.sciencestorm.com/award/0345314.html |date=2011-07-16 }}</ref>
By law [[Croatian Radiotelevision]] is to promote the translation of programs into HZJ.<ref>[http://www.poslovni-savjetnik.com/propisi/mediji-hrvatska-radiotelevizija/zakon-o-hrvatskoj-radioteleviziji-vazeci-tekst-nn-br-13710 Zakon o Hrvatskoj Radioteleviziji]</ref> Major centres of education in HZJ are found in Zagreb, [[Split, Croatia|Split]], and [[Osijek]].<ref>[http://www.dodir.hr/tecajhzj.php Tečaj HZJ]</ref>
Organizations for the deaf in Croatia include the ''Croatian Association of Deafblind Persons DODIR'', which was established in 1994.<ref>[http://lib.ohchr.org/HRBodies/UPR/Documents/session9/HR/DODIR_HRCroatianAssociationofDeafblindPersons.pdf Croatian Association of Deafblind Persons DODIR]</ref>
The basic word order in HZJ is [[subject–verb–object]] (SVO), as it is in [[Croatian language|spoken Croatian]].<ref>''Information status and word order in Croatian Sign Language'', Clinical Linguistics & Phonetics, November–December 2007; 21(11–12): 1007–1017.</ref> A [[two-handed manual alphabet]] is in widespread use; a one-handed alphabet based on the [[international manual alphabet]], though less commonly used, has official status.<ref name=Bick/><ref>[http://www.dodir.hr/jednorucna.php Single-handed alphabet]</ref><ref>[http://www.hsgn.hr/jednorucnaabeceda.html Jednoručna abeceda]</ref>
